<subSubSection lastPageId="86" lastPageNumber="87" pageId="84" pageNumber="85" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="84.[151,1436,1655,2016]" box="[151,208,1884,1908]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Male</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="84.[151,1436,1655,2016]" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">
<emphasis box="[151,212,1920,1944]" italics="true" pageId="84" pageNumber="85">Head</emphasis>
. Third antennal segment long acuminate; black. Face silvery pollinose. Frons, upper part subshining black, lower part silvery pollinose, except shining black spot in the middle; eyes touching for distance equal to 3.5–4 times ocellar triangle. Occiput, lower half silvery pollinose, upper half more brown.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6039243" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6039243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6039243/files/figure.png" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" startId="85.[151,250,1859,1882]" targetBox="[316,1281,189,1824]" targetPageId="85">
<paragraph blockId="85.[151,1436,1859,2015]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,1859,1882]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">FIGURE 28.</emphasis>
Male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName box="[482,698,1860,1882]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Eudorylas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pectinatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[482,698,1860,1882]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">Eudorylas pectinatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[706,791,1860,1881]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[706,791,1860,1881]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(A–E) and 
<taxonomicName box="[915,1014,1860,1882]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Eudorylas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilulus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[915,1014,1860,1882]" italics="true" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">E. pilulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1022,1106,1860,1881]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1022,1106,1860,1881]" pageId="85" pageNumber="86" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(F–J).—A: outer surstylus with outer gonopod, phallic guide and its projections, lateral view, B: ventral view with phallic guide and phallus (without ST8), C: inner surstylus, lateral view, D: surstyli, dorsal view, E: dorsal view, F: outer surstylus with phallic guide and outer gonopod, lateral view, G: dorsal view, H: inner surstylus, lateral view, I: surstyli, dorsal view, J: ventral view with phallus and phallic guide (without ST8). Scale bars: 0.1 mm
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,151,825]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis box="[151,232,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Thorax</emphasis>
. Humeri brown (slightly paler than mesonotum). Mesonotum (viewed obliquely from front) brownish pollinose, along anterior margin more greyish; silvery pollinose from the side. Scutellum brownish pollinose, without hairs. Dorsocentral hairs short, pale. Halter brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,151,825]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Legs. Trochanters, femora, knees and tibiae brown. Tarsal segments brown, last segment black. Ventroapical row of spines on femora missing. Subapical (distal) spines on first four tibiae present. No anteromedial hairs on 3rd tibia. Hind trochanter covered with short, velvet-like hairs on ventral side. Pulvilli than last tarsal segment.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,151,825]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Wing. Fourth costal section 0.4–0.5 times as long as third costal section. Cross-vein R-M beyond 2/5 of discal cell. Pterostigma fully coloured. Hairs on tegula missing.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,151,825]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis box="[151,483,441,465]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Abdomen (already dissected)</emphasis>
. Viewed obliquely from front tergites (T1,2) brownish pollinose. Hairs dispersed, short and weakly developed. Laterally 3 dark spines on first tergite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,151,825]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
Genitalia. Surstyli asymmetrical, OS with a pointed tip in dorsal view; epandrium elongated; m.a. as wide as 1/3 of ST8 (
<figureCitation box="[217,325,549,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="85.[151,250,1859,1882]" captionTargetBox="[316,1281,189,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-105@85.[245,1342,161,1836]" captionTargetPageId="85" captionText="FIGURE 28. Male genitalia of Eudorylas pectinatus sp. nov. (A–E) and E. pilulus sp. nov. (F–J).—A: outer surstylus with outer gonopod, phallic guide and its projections, lateral view, B: ventral view with phallic guide and phallus (without ST8), C: inner surstylus, lateral view, D: surstyli, dorsal view, E: dorsal view, F: outer surstylus with phallic guide and outer gonopod, lateral view, G: dorsal view, H: inner surstylus, lateral view, I: surstyli, dorsal view, J: ventral view with phallus and phallic guide (without ST8). Scale bars: 0.1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6039243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6039243/files/figure.png" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Fig. 28G</figureCitation>
). SES with hairy ridges on both sides; gonopods short, both with medial lobes (overlapping in ventral view, 
<figureCitation box="[306,404,585,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="85.[151,250,1859,1882]" captionTargetBox="[316,1281,189,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-105@85.[245,1342,161,1836]" captionTargetPageId="85" captionText="FIGURE 28. Male genitalia of Eudorylas pectinatus sp. nov. (A–E) and E. pilulus sp. nov. (F–J).—A: outer surstylus with outer gonopod, phallic guide and its projections, lateral view, B: ventral view with phallic guide and phallus (without ST8), C: inner surstylus, lateral view, D: surstyli, dorsal view, E: dorsal view, F: outer surstylus with phallic guide and outer gonopod, lateral view, G: dorsal view, H: inner surstylus, lateral view, I: surstyli, dorsal view, J: ventral view with phallus and phallic guide (without ST8). Scale bars: 0.1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6039243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6039243/files/figure.png" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Fig. 28F</figureCitation>
), IG with pointed tip; hypandrium with elongated lobes; phallic guide broad, sides parallel, distal part with three pointed appendices (
<figureCitation box="[620,714,621,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="85.[151,250,1859,1882]" captionTargetBox="[316,1281,189,1824]" captionTargetId="figure-105@85.[245,1342,161,1836]" captionTargetPageId="85" captionText="FIGURE 28. Male genitalia of Eudorylas pectinatus sp. nov. (A–E) and E. pilulus sp. nov. (F–J).—A: outer surstylus with outer gonopod, phallic guide and its projections, lateral view, B: ventral view with phallic guide and phallus (without ST8), C: inner surstylus, lateral view, D: surstyli, dorsal view, E: dorsal view, F: outer surstylus with phallic guide and outer gonopod, lateral view, G: dorsal view, H: inner surstylus, lateral view, I: surstyli, dorsal view, J: ventral view with phallus and phallic guide (without ST8). Scale bars: 0.1 mm" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6039243" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6039243/files/figure.png" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Fig. 28J</figureCitation>
); phallus trifid, coiled.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,151,825]" box="[151,379,657,681]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Female—Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="86" pageNumber="87" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="86.[151,1436,151,825]" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">
<emphasis box="[151,249,693,717]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">Remarks</emphasis>
—Similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Foldvari" authorityYear="2003" box="[394,531,694,717]" class="Insecta" family="Pipunculidae" genus="Eudorylas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="86" pageNumber="87" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="swanengi">
<emphasis box="[394,531,694,717]" italics="true" pageId="86" pageNumber="87">E. swanengi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but phallus long, curved, OG larger than IG, with pointed tip; SES not very well developed, arms of surstyli smaller.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
